<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-976-848  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 976 848.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Dec 18 1989 v6 n50 p42(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Alloy lets Macs, PCs share files across its multiuser 386 OS.andO;(Alloy Computer Products Inc.'s Mac-Attach and Link-PC emulationsoftware) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Morrissey, Jane.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Alloy Computer Products Inc. (product introduction).andO;Ticker:    ALOY.andO;Product:   Link-PC (Emulation software) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionEmulationSoftware packages.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Jane MorrisseyandM;Alloy Computer Products Inc. is delivering new versions of itsterminal-emulation software aimed at Macintosh users who want a low-cost wayto run DOS applications in a multiuser environment.andM;The company's new Mac-Attach and Link-PC programs now work with 386/MultiWare-- Alloy's DOS-based multiuser, multitasking system that supports up to 21users -- allowing Macs to participate for the first time in a 386-basedmultiuser environment along with other PCs and terminals.andM;Under this scenario, a Mac will be able to share files and access peripheralsresiding on a 386 PC, perform ASCII file transfers with PCs or terminals onthe system, and access DOS applications within the full Macintosh graphicaluser interface, according to officials at the Marlboro, Mass., firm.andM;The combination of Mac-Attach and 386/MultiWare provides an economical andstable solution for furnishing engineers on an Apple Computer Inc.andP;  AppleTalkLAN with access to PC-based manufacturing software, according to users at onebeta site.andM;&quot;Until Mac-Attach, we couldn't find a reliable product to connect Macs to thePCs,&quot; said Steve Dahl, president of AMCI Computers, a dealer andmanufacturing systems integrator in Amery, Wis.andP;  &quot;[Workstations] would eitherhang up unexpectedly, or users could definitely tell they were in the DOSenvironment.&quot;andM;The new $195 Link-PC version 3.0 permits PC users to switch between local andnetwork processing, and now allows CGA-, EGA- or VGA-equipped PCs to act as386/MultiWare terminals, officials said.andP;  Mac-Attach version 2.0, also pricedat $195, provides similar functionality on the Macintosh side.andM;Alloy Computer Products Inc. can be contacted at (508) 481-8500.andO;</TEXT></DOC>